In [47]:
# find the covariance matrix : A^T.A
sample_data = standardized_data
# matrix multiplication using numpy to calculate co variance 
covar_matrix = np.matmul(sample_data.T , sample_data)

print('the shape of covariance matrix = ', covar_matrix.shape)

the shape of covariance matrix =  (784, 784)
In [48]:
# Doing PCA 
from scipy.linalg import eigh 

# the parameter "eigvals" is defined (law value to high value)
# eigh function will return the eigen values in ascending order 
# this code generates only the top 2 (782,783) eigen values.

values, vectors = eigh(covar_matrix, eigvals=(782,783))
print('Shape of eigen vectors=', vectors.shape)
# converting the eigen vestors into (2,d) for easyness of further computation 
vectors = vectors.T
print('Updated shape of eigen vectors =', vectors.shape)

# here the vectors [1] represent corresponding to first principal eigen vectors
# here the vectors [2] represent corresponding to second principal eigen vectors

Shape of eigen vectors= (784, 2)
Updated shape of eigen vectors = (2, 784)
In [49]:
# our objective is to represent 784d into 2d 
# projecting the original data sample onto plane 
# formed by two principal eigen vectors by vector-vector multiplication 

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
new_coordinates = np.matmul(vectors, sample_data.T)

print("resulatnt new data points' shape ", vectors.shape, "X" , sample_data.T.shape, '=', new_coordinates.shape)

resulatnt new data points' shape  (2, 784) X (784, 20000) = (2, 20000)

PCA using scikit learn¶

In [53]:
from sklearn import decomposition 
pca = decomposition.PCA()
In [54]:
# configuring the parameters 
# the Number of components = 2 
pca.n_components = 2
pca_data= pca.fit_transform(sample_data)

# Here we feed our sample data into PCA .fit_transform this function alone will do all the computations
# which we did earlier like Covariance matrix, eigen values and eigen vectors (top 2 )

# pca_reduced will contain 2-d projection of simple data 
print('shape of pca_reduced.shape=', pca_data.shape)

shape of pca_reduced.shape= (20000, 2)

PCA for dimensionality reduction ( not Visualization )¶

In [57]:
# PCA for dimensionality reduction (non - visualisation )
pca.n_components = 784
pca_data = pca.fit_transform(sample_data)

percentage_var_explained = pca.explained_variance_ / np.sum(pca.explained_variance_);

cum_var_explained = np.cumsum(percentage_var_explained)

# Plot the PCA spectrum 
plt.figure(1, figsize=(6,4))

plt.clf()
plt.plot(cum_var_explained, linewidth = 2)
plt.axis('tight')
plt.grid()
plt.xlabel("n_components")
plt.ylabel("Cummulative_explained_variance")
plt.show()
In [58]:
 # From this graph we can actuallu tell that if we need to obtain 90%age variance explained we will need around 200 features 
    # this is very useful for our ML algorithms .

Visualizing of MNIST dataset using t-SNE¶

In [59]:
#TSNE 
from sklearn.manifold import TSNE 
# picking the top 1000 points as TSNE takes a lot of time for 20k points to run 
data_1k = standardized_data[0:1000:]
labels_1k = labels[0:1000]

model = TSNE(n_components = 2, random_state=0)
#configuring the parameter 
#the number of components = 2
# default perplexity = 30
# default learning rate = 200
# default Maximum number of iterations for optimization = 1000
tsne_data = model.fit_transform(data_1k)

# creating a new data which help us in plotting the result data 
tsne_data = np.vstack((tsne_data.T, labels_1k)).T
tsne_df = pd.DataFrame(data= tsne_data, columns=('Dim_1','Dim_2','label'))

# plotting the result of tsne 
sn.FacetGrid(tsne_df,hue="label",size=10).map(plt.scatter, 'Dim_1', 'Dim_2').add_legend()
plt.show()
